author: darin.yoga
caption:
Want a straighter, stronger handstand?
‚úèÔ∏è So hear me out:
Improving handstand alignment starts with understanding the positioning of the rib cage and shoulders.
‚†Ä
BUT!
To stack your pelvis over your shoulders, you need to start with the right support- not the wall ‚ùå
* every time I see total beginners being told to ‚Äújust work on the wall‚Äù‚Ä¶ I want to cry ü•≤
‚†Ä
‚úÖ Begin with lower support (gym box, chair, sofa).
It teaches your body the shape without crushing you with fear or bad habits.
‚†Ä
But‚Ä¶ even this can feel impossible at first.
Why? Compression üòà
‚†Ä
That moment when you‚Äôre trying to pull your quads in, hips close to the belly‚Ä¶
‚Ä¶and suddenly your shoulders say ‚ÄúNope‚Äù and give up on flexing?
‚†Ä
üí° That‚Äôs not you being ‚Äúbad at handstands‚Äù- it‚Äôs simply weak delts and traps that can‚Äôt hold the load yet.
‚†Ä
Here‚Äôs my fix:
‚úÖ Switch to higher support (tall box or kitchen table).
‚†Ä
This removes compression, makes your legs light, and lets you focus on the real alignment game:
‚Ä¢ Shoulders stacked right above your palms
‚Ä¢ Ribs down, abs on and practice the full exhalation to the bottom of your belly
‚†Ä
Master this first ‚Üí then move to lower support ‚Üí then the floor.
‚†Ä
üî• Your shoulders will get stronger, your line cleaner, and your handstand will stop feeling like a fight.

author: coach.bluee
caption:
Is benching a bar off your chest real strength?

Look yes obviously pushing a bar off your chest requires strength. 
but when I say benching is not real strength I am talking to people who cares about having control over their own body more than a stable, perfect scenario exercise like the bench press. 
Anyone can push a bar off their chest
Now tell me why less than 0.0001% of people can do a planche even less a planche  push-up 
That‚Äôs because a planche test your relative strength (strength proportional to your body weight)
Now tell me why are we not more interested in having strength over our own body weight than we are of pushing a bar off our chest. 
The answer is simple but painful for many. 
Which is the reason why many hate on the message I preach‚Ä¶
‚ÄúBecause it‚Äôs hard and they can‚Äôt do it‚Äù
But‚Ä¶ I can‚Äôt do it because I don‚Äôt practice it. 
No sir you can‚Äôt do it because you can‚Äôt even  fathom the idea of how that‚Äôs even possible. 

Here are some of the required strength for a planche‚Ä¶
Balance, significant core strength, stability, shoulder strength, wrist strength, leg strength and stability, straight arm strength. 

A bench press‚Ä¶
Neutral spine. Stable external load. Lying on a bench. Feet planted. 

I will let you decide for yourself which one is harder and requires more guts to even begin to try. And is more useful strength in the real world. 

Before you ask. I was never a gymnast. I just decided to work on real strength. 
Calisthenics strength.

author: trainbloom
caption:
Bro split = vaulted

Unless you‚Äôre brand new to the gym, training each muscle only once per week probably isn‚Äôt cutting it anymore

After that, there‚Äôs no single ‚Äúbest‚Äù split 

Just the one that fits you best based on a few key questions:

1. Can you hit each muscle 2+ times per week?
2. Can you train hard without recovery bleeding into the next session?
3. Can you stick to it consistently?
4. Does it match your main goal (strength, size, or both?)

Once those are answered, here‚Äôs what usually works best depending on how many days you can train each weeküëá

3 Day Splits:
- Full Body X3
- Upper/Lower + Full Body

4 Day Splits:
- Upper/Lower X2
- Full Body X4
- Push/Pull/Leg + Full Body

5 Day Splits:
- Push/Pull/Leg + Full X2
- Full + Upper/Lower X2
- Push/Pull/Leg + Upper/Lower

Remember, at the end of the day any of these splits will work as long as you do üëäüèº

Great original stitched video from @chloe_jayne._ 

Study cited:
The Resistance Training Dose-Response: Meta-Regressions Exploring the EÔ¨Äects of Weekly Volume and Frequency on Muscle Hypertrophy and Strength Gain

author: trainbloom
caption:
What does ashwagandha actually do?

(probably more than you think üßê)

Ashwagandha is an adaptogen, meaning it helps the body adapt to stress

And it does this by being the single best non-drug compound at reducing levels of cortisol in the body (our main stress hormone)

The only problem with taking ashwagandha long-term is that cortisol isn‚Äôt always a bad thing‚Ä¶

Actually, it‚Äôs essential (like you would die without it)

So taking ashwagandha to handle short-term stressors in life (4-12 weeks), like when work is crazy and you‚Äôre barely sleeping, or you‚Äôre going through a heavy training block at the gym is the best way to take it before cycling back off.

IMPORTANT NOTES ON HOW TO TAKE:

The most common way to take ashwagandha is taking between 300-600mg of root extract, 1-2x per day (in the morning and at night) for 4-12 weeks at a time before taking time off.

Ashwagandha is one of the most commonly faked or mislabelled supplements on the market, so be sure to get one that‚Äôs 3rd party tested

Some solid brands that do that are:

- Legion Athletics (600mg - also in my bio)
- Transparent Labs (600mg)
- Nutricost (600mg)

(these aren‚Äôt the only ones that exist, just the ones I‚Äôve found and trust)

author: trainbloom
caption:
Does fasted cardio burn more fat?

Yes (during the workout‚Ä¶)

When you train fasted (low insulin), your body uses more fat than carbs for fuel

When you train fed (after eating), it uses more carbs

But here‚Äôs the catch:

Burning fat ‚â† Losing fat

Your body balances that out over 24 hours

If you burn more fat during the workout, you‚Äôll burn less later

If you burn more carbs during the workout, you‚Äôll burn more fat later

So by the end of the day, total body fat burned is about the same

The real driver of fat loss is whether those calories you burn push you into a calorie deficit, not whether you trained fasted or fed

Bonus tip:

Working out fasted too long increases muscle breakdown (not good)

If it‚Äôs been several hours since you‚Äôve eaten, grab a small snack first

And if you can‚Äôt stomach food, 1‚Äì3g of HMB can help offset that muscle loss

Studies/Research:
PMID:¬†27609363
PMID:¬†15896087

author: trainbloom
caption:
Placebo = Very real 

What you *think* can literally change how your body reacts to food on a hormonal level

In this study, every participant drank the exact same milkshake

Same calories. Same ingredients. Same taste

But the twist? 

Researchers told half of them it was a healthier, low-calorie ‚Äúsensible‚Äù shake

While the others were told it was a high-calorie, high-sugar, high-fat ‚Äúdelectable‚Äù milkshake

Most people would assume their bodies would respond the same, since the same nutrients were going in

But that‚Äôs not what happened‚Ä¶

The group who *thought* they were drinking the unhealthier shake saw a 3x greater drop in the hunger hormone ghrelin compared to those who thought they were drinking the healthier version

Aka: their bodies responded as if they consumed more food,
even though it was the exact same shake both times

Your mind is more powerful than you probably give it credit for

Be careful what you think

Milkshake Study:
PMID:¬†21574706

#fitness #gym #workout #supplements #creatine

author: trainbloom
caption:
25g of creatine?

Most people consider 5g per day to be the standard dose of creatine

But more and more research is looking at what happens when you take more than that (sometimes, a LOT more)

It turns out that increasing your dose may impact a lot more than just muscle

Things like:
* Mental health and depression
* Combating sleep deprivation
* Cognition (memory, reaction time, focus, etc.)
* And more

In the study from this reel, people who took 25g of creatine after being awake for 21 hours not only erased the negative effects of sleep deprivation, they actually outperformed their own well-rested baseline scores

But before you go chug five scoops, taking 25g daily can cause some nasty side effects like cramping, bloating, and stomach issues

Other research shows you can get most of the same brain benefits at around 10‚Äì16g per day, without the downsides

So:
‚Üí 5g/day = full muscle benefits + small cognition boost
‚Üí 10‚Äì16g/day = adds cognitive perks
‚Üí 25g/day = helps acutely with sleep loss, but probably not worth the gut ache

Research from reel:

author: trainbloom
caption:
How much protein in one meal is too much?

The answer: We still haven‚Äôt found the upper limit‚Ä¶

There‚Äôs an old myth that your body can only ‚Äúuse‚Äù 20‚Äì30g of protein in one meal, and that the rest just goes to waste or stored as fat (also wrong)

But over time, as researchers have actually tested this, and that number has never really held up

In a recent study testing this again, 100g of protein in one sitting STILL increased muscle protein synthisis significantly more than just 40g (study linked below)

On top of this, when you other research comparing groups of people who either eat all of their protein in 1-2 big meals vs. people who spead their protein out through the day, they both see nearly identical progress in terms of muscle

Now could there be a small benefit to spreading your protein out more evenly?
Yes‚Ä¶ (but emphasis on *small*ü§èüèº)

If you‚Äôre really trying to squeeze an extra few percent out of the effect protein has on your body, are training twice a day, or eating a LOT of protein daily, it can give you a tiny boost (1-2%)
But for most people, just hitting your total protein target each day will get you 99% of the way there

So if you‚Äôre stressing about the ‚Äúperfect‚Äù protein timing‚Ä¶ don‚Äôt
Just eat enough, consistently, and everything will work out

author: trainbloom
caption:
Stubborn fat is real, and here‚Äôs why it feels impossible to lose

Some fat cells on your body are literally harder to shrink than others
Not because you‚Äôre doing anything wrong, but because the fat in areas like your lower stomach, love handles, and thighs have more of what are called alpha-2 receptors

(basically, the more of these receptors a fat cell has, the more resistant it is to letting go fat for energy)

That‚Äôs why these spots don‚Äôt budge, even when everything else is changing

But they don‚Äôt defy physics, you can lose stubborn fat

You just can‚Äôt choose where you lose it first
Your body burns the easy-to-access fat first, and saves the harder to burn ‚Äústubborn‚Äù fat for last

So getting rid of stubborn fat really comes down to two things:
1. being in a big enough calorie deficit
2. and staying in it long enough for your body to finally reach those harder-to-burn areas

There are no hacks, shortcuts, sor supplements around that
Just the actual physiology of how fat loss works

Great stitched reel by @trizzlemanfitness 

#gym #fitness #workout

author: trainbloom
caption:
So that‚Äôs not how your metabolism works‚Ä¶

If you had to exercise to burn off every calorie you put in your mouth, you‚Äôd be on the treadmill 24 hours a day üíÄ

Because even if you put WORK in at the gym, it still only accounts for the smallest portion of where you burn calories in a day (<5-10%)

You‚Äôre not a dog that has to earn it‚Äôs treat

And our bodies just don‚Äôt work like that

It‚Äôs a million times more productive to use exercise to help build the other pieces up, increasing your metabolic output as a whole

Work smarter, not harder ü§ùüèº

author: trainbloom
caption:
How many rest days should you be taking?

Honestly, more than most people think.

You don‚Äôt build muscle by lifting weights, you build muscle by recovering from lifting weights

But recovery isn‚Äôt just ‚Äúdays off‚Äù

Recovery = sleep + food + hydration + stress management + days off

How well (or poorly) you‚Äôre doing on those is what determines how many rest days you actually need

For most people, 3-5 hard, well-structured sessions will build more muscle than cramming in 6-7

This is one part of life where sometimes, less is more

#gym #workout #recovery #muscle #strength

author: trainbloom
caption:
How long should you rest between sets?

It depends‚Ä¶ (but probably longer than you think)

If you want all of the benefits of strength training (e.g. increased metabolism, getting stronger, making fat loss MUCH easier, etc.)

You have to actually‚Ä¶ STRENGTH train‚Ä¶

One of the most common mistakes I see people make when their goal is to lose weight, is by turning their weight training into cardio 

(e.g. using light weights, high reps only, and taking 30-60s rest between sets)

If you want to build more strength, more size, and equal endurance, you should be resting at LEAST more than 1 minute between your sets

For a better breakdown, I recommend basing it off of what muscle group you‚Äôre training

Smaller muscle groups: rest between 90-seconds and 2-minutes (arms, shoulders, calves, abs, etc.)

Larger muscle groups: rest 2-3 minutes (chest, back, legs, etc.)

‚ÄºÔ∏èBUT HERE‚ÄôS THE ONLY IMPORTANT PART

No matter the muscle group, the goal for how much rest you take should be to not have your last set negatively impact the set you‚Äôre about to do

Remember, it‚Äôs very easy to rest too little, but very hard to rest too much

And if you think you need less than a minute to make that possible, I would bet money that you‚Äôre just not lifting heavy enough. 

Great originial video from @pathradecha

author: trainbloom
caption:
How fast do you lose muscle?

(when taking time off the gym)

1 month? 1 week? 1 DAY?!

Not quite

It feels like you lose 1+ month of gains every time you miss a workout

The good news is, it takes a bit longer than that until you start losing muscle (at least 2-3+ weeks completely off the gym)

But what if you take longer than that off, and you do end up losing some?

Well, that does suck

But it‚Äôs not as bad as you probably think, because of something called muscle memory

Or the permanent changes that take place in your muscle cells when you build it the first time, that make regaining muscle you once had happen a LOT quicker than it did building in the first place

Anywhere from 2-3x+ faster

So what took you a few months to build initially, might only take several weeks to regain once you start again

author: trainbloom
caption:
Fat burning zone ‚â† Fat *loss zone

YES, your body can shift between burning more carbs or more fat for fuel during a workout‚Ä¶

But that doesn‚Äôt actually change how much body fat you‚Äôll lose

Here‚Äôs why:

Your body balances things out over 24 hours

If you burn more fat during a workout, you‚Äôll burn less fat later (and more carbs instead)

If you burn more carbs, you‚Äôll burn more fat later

Example:

30 mins of sprints = ~500 calories, mostly carbsvs. 
90 mins incline walk = ~500 calories, mostly fat

But at the end of the day, roughly the same amount of body fat lost

Because the real driver of fat loss is whether those calories push you into a deficit

Not the mix of fat vs carbs you burned in the moment

Incline walking isn‚Äôt bad, I actually love it

It‚Äôs lower impact, easier to recover from, doesn‚Äôt spike hunger as much

It‚Äôs the perfect tool if you enjoy it

Just remember: the best cardio for fat loss is what you like the most (or hate the least), since that‚Äôs what you‚Äôll actually be consistent with

Shout out to @ob_health.fit for sending me the video to stitch the beginning üëäüèº

author: trainbloom
caption:
Your metabolism doesn‚Äôt slow down when you get older

At least, not as soon as you think‚Ä¶

Duke University recently finished up one of the biggest studies on human metabolism ever done

Testing our metabolic rates starting at 8-days old, all the way up to 95-years old to see how it changes through a lifetime

They found that dependent on lean mass (muscle), that your metabolism doesn‚Äôt start to slow down until after you turn 60 years old‚Ä¶ 

But from 20 years old until then, it basically stayed the same 

This doesn‚Äôt mean that losing weight doesn‚Äôt get harder for most people after 20-30 years old,

It usually does‚Ä¶

But it‚Äôs not because of your age

It‚Äôs because your life and habits change

After high-school/college you typically get a job where you‚Äôre sitting all day, you stop working out as much, you start eating a lot more, sleeping less, etc.

All things that make you burn less calories (at any age‚Ä¶)

To keep your metabolism high, or build it back up, you don‚Äôt need to defy biology

You need the *right* basic habits in place

- Lifting heavy weights 3-4x per week 
- Getting 8-10k+ steps per day
- Eating a high protein diet

And don‚Äôt ignore your sleep and stress

Do the simple things consistently well, and you‚Äôd be shocked at how far it gets you

Great OG post by @szatpayton 

STUDY:
Daily Energy Expenditure Through The Human Life Course
https://www.science.org/doi/10.1126/science.abe5017

author: trainbloom
caption:
Cardio before OR after lifting weights?

They‚Äôre almost pulling you in two different directions‚Ä¶

Lifting weights is what‚Äôs called ‚Äúanabolic‚Äù

Basically meaning it puts your body into ‚Äúbuild-mode‚Äù

Where cardio is catabolic

Basically meaning it puts your body into ‚Äúbreakdown-mode‚Äù

So if you‚Äôre not careful, it‚Äôs almost like hitting the gas and the breaks at the same time when it comes to building muscle and getting stronger

That‚Äôs why some people recommend splitting up cardio and weights, doing one in the morning and one in the afternoon

But let‚Äôs be real‚Ä¶ Who has time for that?

And if you‚Äôre smart about it, that‚Äôs completely unnecessary

Here‚Äôs what you need to do to make sure that doesn‚Äôt happen:

1. If you‚Äôre doing cardio in the same workouts as weights, make sure you do it after

This will make sure you are strongest for the most important part of the workout (lifting weights)

2. Limit it to under 20-30 minutes max

Once you go past that mark, it will start to block important muscle building signals

3. Opt for lower intensity instead of higher intensity forms that rack up fatigue

(e.g. inline walking, cycling, stair climbing instead of things like sprints or HIIT)

And bonus tip, have a small pre-workout meal 1-2 hours before your workout with protein and carbs, or if you‚Äôre training fasted 1-3g of HMB supplement will help prevent muscle breakdown

STUDIES FROM REEL:

author: trainbloom
caption:
Your cardio isn‚Äôt ‚Äúbroken‚Äù‚Ä¶

It‚Äôs actually just doing its job too well

Because the more you repeat the same run, bike, class, etc.
The better your body gets at it

(aka it burns fewer calories to do the same job)

That‚Äôs not bad news either, that‚Äôs literally the point of exercise: to get better at what you‚Äôre doing

The only catch is that if you‚Äôre banking on the calories from cardio to keep you in a deficit, you‚Äôll eventually hit a wall

Which is why cardio is GREAT for:
‚û°Ô∏è Stronger heart & lungs‚û°Ô∏è Better energy & recovery‚û°Ô∏è Longer life (semi-important)

And why muscle (and all the other parts of your day) are the metabolism upgrade you actually want

It‚Äôs not just about calories during the workout

Cardio‚Äôs great, just don‚Äôt lean on it alone for fat loss

@deannadang_

author: trainbloom
caption:
Can eating too little ever make you gain weight?

Not really

The idea that your metabolism ‚Äòbreaks‚Äô from undereating making it impossible to lose weight simply isn‚Äôt true

Even in the harshest starvation studies, metabolism slowed, but never to the point of reversing fat loss

You don‚Äôt gain weight from eating too little

Here are 5 real reasons you think you‚Äôre in a deficit, but aren‚Äôt:

1. You‚Äôre measuring progress on too short of a timeline. The scale is a lagging indicator of your habits. 7‚Äì14 days isn‚Äôt enough for it to represent what you‚Äôve been doing.

2. Food tracking errors. Food tracking is a skill and it‚Äôs easy to mess up. A ‚Äúlogged‚Äù deficit doesn‚Äôt guarantee a real one

3. You‚Äôre eating a LOT more untracked calories than you think. (e.g. weekends, cheat meals, etc.). A Mon‚ÄìThurs deficit erased by Fri‚ÄìSun overeating is the most common trap

4. You‚Äôre overestimating exercise burn. Watches and trackers drastically inflate how many calories you burned during a workout. (up to 90% innacurate)

5. Your habits suck. Poor sleep, high stress, and sitting all day can quietly drop your calorie burn

The only reason ‚Äúeating too little‚Äù can lead to weight gain, is if it‚Äôs making you eat *too much* over a longer period of time

Studies from reel:
PMID:¬†25905303
PMID:¬†20518700

author: trainbloom
caption:
Raw Milk = Overrated

Just because something is ‚Äúnatural‚Äù doesn‚Äôt mean it‚Äôs healthier for you

If you want:
- Less vitamins and nutrients
- More pus, bacteria, and pathogens
- And a 45X higher chance of hospitalization

Then raw milk is for YOU ü´µüèº

But if you‚Äôre sane, pasteurized milk at the store is the better option

There‚Äôs two more myths about raw milk I didn‚Äôt have time to cover in the video:

Myth 1: ‚ÄúPasturization kills all the ‚Äúgood‚Äù bacteria in milk‚Äù

This one‚Äôs actually true... but it doesn‚Äôt matter, and here‚Äôs why:

Because although yes, pasturization kills a tiny amount of beneficial bacteria in the milk‚Ä¶

The amount of beneficial bacteria lost is too small to impact your health in the slightest, and pasteurization kills dangerous pathogens like salmonella, listeria, and E. coli.

In fact, you get way more good bacteria from a cup of yogurt or a few slices of cheese than you do in a cup of raw milk (without the risk)

Myth 2: ‚ÄúPasturization denatures the protein‚Äôs in milk making it harder to digest‚Äù

Again, this is true‚Ä¶ but the same people who shout this forget to mention that our stomach acid denatures ALL proteins anyway

So from a physiological standpoint, this means absolutely nothing

Please don‚Äôt spend 10X more money falling for another health trend that could land you in the hospital, with zero potential upside

author: trainbloom
caption:
No, the aspartame in diet coke isn‚Äôt killing you

If you want an easy way to spot bad nutrition advice, remember this:

The dose makes the poison.

It applies to everything (even the ‚Äúscary‚Äù ingredients you can‚Äôt pronounce on a label)

But the key detail most people leave out: How much is actually in the product

Because it‚Äôs not the presence of a thing that makes it harmful, it‚Äôs the amount

Even the healthiest things in the world can become dangerous in the wrong dose

‚Üí One sip of water won‚Äôt save your life

‚Üí But a liter every hour can end it

And with artificial sweeteners like aspartame, the dose you‚Äôd need to reach a harmful level?

You‚Äôd get water poisoning first

That‚Äôs not an exaggeration, it‚Äôs literally been tested

This isn‚Äôt to say aspartame is good, or that you need Diet Coke

Just that most fear-based health content leaves out the actual science and replaces it with panic, because panic gets clicks

author: trainbloom
caption:
Your Apple Watch (or Whoop, or Oura, etc.) is lying to you

These devices are awesome for steps, sleep, even recovery‚Ä¶ but calories burned?

They‚Äôre basically just guessing

But it‚Äôs not the technology‚Äôs fault

Right now, the BEST these devices can do is plug in a few things they can track:

* heart rate
* age
* gender
* weight
* workout type

‚Ä¶and run an equation to spit out a number

But here‚Äôs where it falls apart:
They can‚Äôt factor in your hormones, genetics, how much you slept last night‚Ä¶ plus about 100 other variables that all change how many calories you really burn

Until your watch can run genome testing and blood work, it‚Äôll never be ‚Äúaccurate‚Äù

The good news though, is that doesn‚Äôt matter

Because the calories burned during your workout make up less than 5% of what you burn in a week

Which means tweaking your intake based on yesterday‚Äôs workout is a complete waste of time

Instead, look at the bigger picture: track your intake, watch how your scale trends over time, and adjust from there

author: trainbloom
caption:
Plant-Based vs. Animal-Based Protein (Part 1)

This is a topic I‚Äôve genuinely changed my mind on over the years
(Even if it hasn‚Äôt changed my behavior much, I still lean toward an animal-based diet for a few reasons)

I used to think plant-based proteins were basically useless

Most of them are incomplete, or missing one or more of the 9 essential amino acids, and I assumed that meant they were worse for muscle growth

But health isn‚Äôt always what it looks like on paper.

Because today, multiple studies have shown that when total daily protein is matched (typically ~1.6‚Äì1.8g/kg of body weight)

Plant-based and animal-based groups build the same amount of muscle and strength

So does that mean plant proteins are just as good?

Not exactly

It‚Äôs way harder to hit 150g of protein eating only plants compared to animals
Most plant sources are low in protein per calorie and less convenient overall, which makes consistently hitting your protein target much tougher

But when people do hit those numbers?
Plant protein works just fine

‚ö†Ô∏è Important note:
This is specifically talking about protein quality

It‚Äôs not the same conversation as a vegan diet vs. an omnivorous diet

Because a diet is more than just protein‚Ä¶

It includes micronutrients, food variety, total calorie intake, bioavailability, gut health, long-term sustainability, and more

So even though plant protein can match animal protein in a muscle-building context (when enough is consumed), that doesn‚Äôt automatically mean a fully vegan diet is nutritionally equivalent to an omnivorous one (or optimal for everyone)

That‚Äôs a much bigger conversation for another video

author: trainbloom
caption:
How to lose fat AND build muscle at the same time

(aka, body recomp)

We *used to think* body recomp was only possible for a very small group of people

(people who were either very obese, brand new to lifting, or taking performance enhancing drugs/steroids)

But after years of seeing it happen with my own clients, talking to other coaches, and seeing it confirmed in countless studies (linked below)

We now know that body recomp is a very realistic goal for most people

Traditional cutting and bulking phases can be a little quicker for body composition change, but they each have drawbacks.

For cutting: You need a larger calorie deficit, your workouts usually get weaker over time, and you typically feel worse the longer it goes. Not impossible to push through, but much harder to stay consistent for a lot of people.

For bulking: You often gain a noticeable amount of fat along with muscle, which for some makes workouts, daily life, and self-image worse.

For those reasons, body recomp can be a better solution for more people than they realize.

Yes, it might take a little longer, but most people enjoy it more and stick with it longer, which is what actually delivers results.

Because consistency > everything

There‚Äôs also a free protein & calorie calculator in my bio if you need help figuring out how much you need there

author: trainbloom
caption:
Is fish oil worth the hype?

I think so.

Fish oil is mostly known for its benefits to heart health and inflammation
(which it does a phenomenal job at)

Here (in the video) are 3 places it makes a BIG difference that aren‚Äôt talked about as much.

But the two important nutrients you get from fish oil that play a role in almost everything you do are EPA & DHA (both omega-3s).

The problem with most fish oil supplements is that they contain barely any of those at all
(meaning you‚Äôd have to take 20+ pills to actually get enough to make a difference)

The clinical dose for most benefits is 1-2g+ of combined EPA + DHA per day.

Some supplements that hit that are:

* Triton by Legion Athletics (2g - also in my bio)
* Ultra-Omega by Nordic Naturals (1.2g)
* Omega-3 Elixir by Gorilla Mind (2g)

(These aren‚Äôt the only ones that exist, just the ones I‚Äôve found. To be sure, just check that the EPA and DHA on the back of any bottle adds up to over 1-2g.)

author: trainbloom
caption:
Alcohol and weight loss

Usually not best friends‚Ä¶

But probably not for the reason you think‚Ä¶

Because alchol itself *can‚Äôt* be stored as body fat üßê

What leads to you gaining fat from drinking too much is more because of ALL the indirect s*** that come with it

Here‚Äôs a few examples:

1. It‚Äôs loaded with calories, but fills you up like air. So it‚Äôs easy to go overboard without realizing you‚Äôve just chugged half your daily intake.

2. It wrecks your sleep. Even one drink can reduce sleep quality by 20‚Äì30%, making fat loss and muscle gain way harder. 

3. The next-day slump is real. One drink the night before leads to less energy, less motivation, worse workouts, and less total movement through the day, and that adds up fast.

4. It messes with your hormones. Testosterone, estrogen, cortisol, GH, insulin, are all thrown off. It‚Äôs like slamming on the breaks for losing fat or building muscle.

5. And finally, it lowers inhibitions, and spikes your appetite. You might think you‚Äôre in control‚Ä¶ until you‚Äôre 3 drinks deep and halfway through a pizza. This doesn‚Äôt automatically mean you‚Äôll eat like an a**hole, but I haven‚Äôt met someone who drinks regularly that can be consistent with their diet for more than a few days at a time.

Yes, alcohol messes with how your body burns and stores fat

But that‚Äôs honestly the least of your worries when it comes to drinking while trying to make physical progress

Alcohol is not good for you in any amount

But this isn‚Äôt some sort of lecture, I have 1-2 drinks on a few weekends here and there because I like it, and it adds to certain experiences

1-2 infrequent drinks won‚Äôt ruin your progress (alone)

It‚Äôs what comes with it that leads to the real problems

#fitness #gym #workout #health

author: trainbloom
caption:
Does height impact strength? (Yes)

There are TONS of factors that affect how hard a lift is besides heigh

(like muscle mass, insertion points, joint angles, limb proportions, technique‚Ä¶ the list goes on and on)

So the examples in this video are generalizations, assuming everything else is identical (which, let‚Äôs be honest, it never is)

But here‚Äôs the point:

Your skeleton and the structure you‚Äôre working with does influence how you progress in the gym

3 Main Ways Height Plays a Role:

1. Strength-to-Weight ratio

Shorter lifters tend to have higher relative strength (how strong they are compared to their bodyweight) because their levers work in their favor

2. Muscle Building Potential

Your frame size determines how much muscle you can carry

For every 1 lb of bone, your body can hold about ~5lbs of muscle (rough estimate)

That means people with bigger frames often have a higher ceiling for how much total muscle they can end up buliding

3. Range of Motion and Fatigue

Taller lifters travel farther each rep

Longer limbs = longer bar path = more work done

So for compound movements like squats, bench press, deadlifts, etc., the increased range of motion means more fatigue each set (even if strength is equal)

This is why slightly adjusting to lower rep ranges for taller individuals can be helpful

#fitness #gym #workout #tall

author: trainbloom
caption:
Cardio vs. Lifting Weights

Who wins?

Cardio will absolutely help you lose weight
But here‚Äôs the catch:
 
Losing weight probably isn‚Äôt your goal‚Ä¶

Your goal is probably to lose body fat, while holding onto or building muscle in the process

(and there‚Äôs a BIG difference)

When you lose muscle, you don‚Äôt get ‚Äúlean‚Äù or add shape

You just get smaller

And research confirms this

But it doesn‚Äôt have to be this OR that

(¬øPor qu√© no los dos?)

You can have both

And when you look at research that shows us what cardio + lifting weights can do together, it almost always outperforms just one or the other

If you want to look ‚Äútone‚Äù, defined, or with shape, you need to be lifting heavy weights

But cardio might help you get there quicker if you sprinkle some on top

Research:
1st study in reel: PMID:¬†10204826
2nd study in reel: PMID:¬†23019316

#gym #fitness #creatine

author: trainbloom
caption:
Do you want to lose weight?

Or do you want to lose fat?

There‚Äôs a BIG difference‚Ä¶

Weight can come from one of two places, either:

1) Body fat

2) Or lean body mass (like muscle/water/etc.)

Although the scale goes down for both, the results look (and feel) a LOT different

If you take the *weight* loss approach and end up losing muscle, water, and a little bit of fat:

- you‚Äôll slow down your metabolism (making it harder to keep losing weight)
- end up with more of a ‚Äúskinny-fat‚Äù look (no definition or tone)
- and most likely regain any weight you do lose as soon as you stop dieting

(that literally all sounds terrible)

But if you take the *fat* loss approach:

- your metabolism will usually increase
- you‚Äôll look leaner and more defined as you lose weight
- and you‚Äôll actually be able to keep the progress you made

(I think that‚Äôs what you actually want‚Ä¶)

Yes, focusing on fat-loss takes a little longer‚Ä¶

Yes, your diet and exercise might look different than what you‚Äôve tried in the past‚Ä¶

But if what you did in the past worked, you wouldn‚Äôt be here now, right?

#gym #workout #fitness #weightloss

author: trainbloom
caption:
What does Vitamin D actually do? ‚òÄÔ∏è

A LOT more than most people realize‚Ä¶

That‚Äôs because vitamin D isn‚Äôt just a vitamin, it a hormone your body produces when sunlight hits your skin

But even if you live in a sunny climate, chances are‚Ä¶ you‚Äôre still not getting enough

50‚Äì70% of the global population is either deficient or insufficient

I live in San Diego, one of the sunniest cities on Earth, and my blood test last year still came back clinically deficient at 18 ng/mL üôÉ

And it matters because low vitamin D doesn‚Äôt just affect your bones or your immune system

‚Üí It impacts your mood
‚Üí Your hormones
‚Üí Your energy
‚Üí Your sleep
‚Üí Literally how your body functions

And from personal experience, supplementing consistently for 3 months made a bigger difference in how I felt than almost anything else I‚Äôve done for my health

One last thing though:

If you do supplement, make sure you‚Äôre also getting vitamin K (specifically K2)
Vitamin D increases calcium absorption, but K2 helps guide it where it belongs (like bones and teeth) instead of places it doesn‚Äôt (like arteries)

So the two work best as a team

I take Legion‚Äôs (in my bio), but Thorne, NOW Foods, and Bulksupplements have good D+K supplements as well

author: trainbloom
caption:
How to fix ‚Äúskinny-fat‚Äù

Most people are trying to solve the wrong problem when it comes to ‚Äúskinny-fat‚Äù

Skinny-fat usually doesn‚Äôt come from having *too much* body fat ‚ùå

It comes from not having enough lean muscle underneath that fat to give your body any shape or definition ‚úÖ

So if you try to fix it by doing everything you can to lose more weight‚Ä¶

e.g. More cardio, less food, etc.

You‚Äôre only going to get further away from your gaol

Instead, try focusing on building lean muscle to give your body shape

By lifting heavy weights 3-5x per week (it won‚Äôt make you bulky, I promise lol)

And instead of obsessing over eating less food, try eating MORE, of the right foods (especially when it comes to protein)

Because you can‚Äôt build living in a calorie deficit

I have a free calorie and protein calculator in my bio if you want to find out an accurate estimate for where you should probably be üßÆ

But remember, every human body is different

So the exact solution for you might need some tweaks, but this should get you going in the right direction

Side note so the comment section doesn‚Äôt get mad: 

This is not saying that there‚Äôs something wrong with this body composition. How someone looks isn‚Äôt good or bad, this video is just here to help people that want to change their physique when they are faced with this common problem.

#skinnyfat #gym #workout

author: trainbloom
caption:
Not how your metabolism works‚Ä¶

(thank godüòÖ)

The stitched video is funny, and technically not wrong‚Ä¶
 
But it‚Äôs not accurate either

Thinking of exercise as just something that burns calories that is a slipper slope (i.e. that you have to ‚Äúearn‚Äù the food you eat with exercise)

But lucky for us, that‚Äôs not how our bodies work

If you had to exercise to burn off every calorie you put in your mouth, you‚Äôd be on the treadmill 24 hours a day

Because even if you put WORK in at the gym, it still only accounts for the smallest portion of where you burn calories in a day

So yes you can do it that way‚Ä¶

But it‚Äôs a million times more productive to use exercise to help build the other pieces up, increasing your metabolic output as a whole

Because lifting weights doesn‚Äôt burn as many calories as cardio does while you‚Äôre in the gym, but it does help you build your BMR (the biggest part of your metabolism, running 24 hours a day)

You could also do things to increase the other parts like eating more protein, which burns 3-10X more calories being digested than carbs or fats do

By moving more and increasing your NEAT, which can burn up to 2,000 EXTRA CALORIES PER DAY - by setting a higher step count goal, or standing instead of sitting at work

Or you could do a lot of other things to build up your BMR up over time like managing your sleep and stress, and getting enough of the important micronutrients through food to make sure your body is running well

Like one of my favorite quotes from Eric Robert‚Äôs on this app: You‚Äôre not a dog trying to earn a treat

Work smarter, not harder ü§ùüèº

Studies:

author: trainbloom
caption:
Smoking vs. Not Lifting Weights?

At this point, not lifting weights, having strength, or moving throughout the day isn‚Äôt optional

We‚Äôve known for years that smoking is one of the worst things you can do for your health

But the crazy part?¬†

Research shows that being in the bottom 20% of strength, or walking less than ~3,000 steps per day compared to the tops of these groups can actually raise your risk of early death even higher¬†

This doesn‚Äôt mean smoking is suddenly ‚Äúsafe‚Äù¬†

(if you want to age faster, feel worse, and increase your risk of almost every disease, smoking cigarettes is a cheat code)

But it does show how badly we underestimate the cost of not moving

Strength training, walking, just getting your body to do the things it was designed to do doesn‚Äôt have to be about building a six-pack, it can at least be about keeping your risk of death from tripling 

Shoutout to @amirsaeedmd who sparked this idea on the topic in an original video

author: trainbloom
caption:
EVERYTHING IS MADE OF CHEMICALS - THATS HOW THE UNIVERSE WORKS BRO 

You, me, a banana, even the AIR, are all just a different combination of chemicals

So saying ‚Äúit has chemicals, therfor it is bad‚Ä¶‚Äù

Is like saying ‚Äòthis alphabet has letters, so it must be an offensive word‚Äù

The letters themselves aren‚Äôt the problem

Sugar free energy drinks aren‚Äôt the healthiest thing for you.

But they‚Äôre not ‚Äúpoison‚Äù either

They‚Äôre mostly just a mix of vitamins, minerals, electrolytes, a small amount of artificial sweetener, and caffeine

And at the doses found in 1 energy drink, none of those are even remotely bad for any healthy person

(caffeine is really the only one you need to keep an eye on, especially if you have heart conditions, are pregnant, or are taking excess caffeine in other parts of your day)

Health is less about what ‚Äúscary-sounding ingredients‚Äù to avoid

And more about asking what you‚Äôre getting from the food you eat

Energy drinks aren‚Äôt the enemy

Bad nutrition advice is

A reminder for the 10th time: no, I‚Äôm not saying energy drinks are healthier than banana‚Äôs. They aren‚Äôt. It‚Äôs just highlighting a common flaw in thinking I see on social media.

author: inflowwithhelene
caption:
This is my short but powerful routine to unlock my hips for straddleü§åüèº 

Start in a sumo squad (goddess pose), playing with both active pulses (15x) and holds (15-30s). 
Then move into pigeon pose: 10-15 leg extensions and 10-15 leg rotations each leg, followed by 10-15 active folds on each leg. 
Lastly sitting in straddle: go through spinal waves in both directions each for ~30-60s. (Leading from your head down forward and up and the other direction is led from the chest forward and down) 

It takes less then 10 minutes of your precious timeü´±üèº‚Äçü´≤üèª

author: madelainerascan
caption:
You‚Äôre not broken. Your metabolism is doing exactly what you trained it to do! 

Metabolism is just how your body creates and uses energy.
It isn‚Äôt fast or slow. It‚Äôs adaptive. 
And the habits you repeat every day are the ones it learns from.

A healthy, strong metabolism is best supported by:
- eating adequate protein (each meal 30-40g)
- Maintaining + building muscle (lift weights 3-4x week)
- Walking daily 
- Sleeping 7-8 hrs
- Not under eating! 
- Eating high quality, whole foods. Metabolism needs the right nutrients to actually produce energy. Whole foods are the most reliable way to get them.

author: madelainerascan
caption:
Stop doing fluffy sh*t.

Listen. These moves are better than sitting on the couch.

And they CAN have a place in a training schedule.
I‚Äôm not a purist. I love some fun full body moves thrown into the mix.

But they can‚Äôt replace the results-driven patterns that actually work.

Otherwise, you end up in the ‚ÄúI work out 4x/week and my body hasn‚Äôt changed an inch‚Äù category.

If you‚Äôre short on time, your workouts need to count.
The movement patterns that never fail and have the power to change your body.

Try this!
3 sets per move.
As many reps as you can, close to failure.
I‚Äôm using 20‚Äì25 lbs here.
-Reverse lunge (L)
-Reverse lunge (R)
-Row (L)
-Row (R)
-Pushup 
-Glute bridge
-Tuck crunch

In 30 minutes or less, you‚Äôll torch your whole body, feel the difference immediately, and see changes 10x faster than the abracadabra IG moves.

Happy training!

PS. I am a qualified Pilates instructor. The opening sentence is always what‚Äôs plastered on top of the viral fitness content from ‚Äúfitness influencers‚Äù. That is not a stab to actual pilates instructors from me.

author: thenutritionreporter
caption:
Food is love, and you can spread it by gifting this to your loved ones! It‚Äôs warm from the spices, cluster-y and so delicious ü©∑üéÑ

INGREDIENTS: 
2 cups oats 
1/3 cup dried cranberries 
¬Ω cup pecans, chopped
¬Ω cup walnuts or hazelnuts, chopped
1/3 cup pumpkin seeds
2 tbsp ground flaxseeds +3-4 tbsp warm water
1/3 cup peanut butter 
¬º-1/3 cup maple syrup (depending on your taste) 
1 tsp pure vanilla extract 

SPICES: 
¬º tsp ground clove 
1 tsp ground ginger 
1 tsp nutmeg 
1 tsp cinnamon 
pinch of sea salt 
 
optional: ¬º cup coconut flakes 

METHOD: 
1. Pre-heat the oven to 160C. Make the flax egg by mixing the ground flax seeds in a bowl with the warm water and set aside.
2.  In a large bowl, mix the dry ingredients, including the oats, chopped walnuts and pecans, the dried cranberries, pumpkin seeds, optional coconut flakes and the spices. 
3. In another smaller bowl, mix the flax egg with the peanut butter, maple syrup and vanilla extract until smooth. Pour this onto the dry oat mix and mix until evenly coated.
4. Spread the granola onto a parchment-lined baking sheet. Use your spatula to push down the granola to allow it to form clusters in the oven.
5. Bake in the oven for around 20 minutes, gently mixing it a little half-way through. The more you mix, the less clusters can form.
6. Wait until fully cooled down before breaking the granola. Store in an air-tight container until consumption.

Everyone reaches for vitamin C the moment a sniffle appears‚Ä¶ but if you actually want to reduce your chances of getting sick in the first place, the science points somewhere else entirely.

This season, think probiotics instead ‚Äì specifically Lactobacillus and Bifidobacteria. The research shows they can help support a more resilient immune system, keep you well for longer, and even shorten how long you‚Äôre out of action if a cold does catch you.

caption:
APPLE PIE PORRIDGE üçéüçÇ for the ultimate cosy breakfast. It will warm and fill you up with fibre, protein, healthy fats and so much joy.

INGREDIENTS
¬Ω cup oats
¬º cup apple puree
¬Ω tsp cinnamon
¬º tsp ground clove
¬Ω tsp ground nutmeg
1 cup milk of your choice
1 tsp pure vanilla extract
1 tbsp ground flaxseeds
Pinch of salt
100g greek-style yoghurt (use high-protein if you can)
Optional scoop of protein powder
1 tbsp nut butter of choice (I used almond butter)

FOR THE APPLE TOPPING
1 red apple
Pinch of cinnamon
Drizzle of maple syrup

METHOD:
1. Start by making the apple topping. Cut the apple into bite-sized pieces and add them to a pan. Drizzle with the maple syrup and some cinnamon. On medium-high heat, fry the apples for a few minutes until they start to caramelize and turn golden (and smell amazing).
2. In a saucepan, mix the oats, plant milk, ground flax, pinch of salt and cook for a few minutes until thick. Depending on the consistency you like, add more or less milk.
3. Once off the heat, add the apple puree, vanilla extract, spices, the optional protein powder and half the greek yogurt. Mix well.
4. Serve in a bowl, top with the rest of the yoghurt, nut butter and the apple toppings. Enjoy!

caption:
This is the ultimate rocky frond recipe üç´ü©∑

INGREDIENTS:

FOR THE CRISPY CHICKPEAS
1 can chickpeas, drained & rinsed
2 large rice cakes
¬º cup goji berries or dried cranberries
¬º cup pistachios 
‚Öì cup macadamia nuts or hazelnuts
2-3 tbsp peanut butter
2 tbsp maple syrup
100g dark chocolate
1 tsp coconut oil

Some chopped pistachios and goji berries to top (optional-chopped peanuts also work)
Pinch of sea salt

METHOD:
1. Pre-heat the oven to 180C (160C-170C fan)
2. Line a baking sheet, add the chickpeas, drizzle with olive oil and pinch of salt. Mix and bake in the oven for around 20 minutes until crispy. 
3. In a large bowl, break up the rice cakes, add the cooled chickpeas, macadamia nuts and mix well. Combine with the peanut butter and maple syrup until everything is evenly coated.
5. Melt the chocolate with the coconut oil in the microwave or double-boiler. Pour over the nut mixture and combine well until everything is coated.
6. Pour mixture onto a lined baking sheet. Using a the back of metal spoon, press down and into a rectangle shape. Top with some crushed pistachios, goji berries (or chopped peanuts) and a pinch of sea salt.
7. Chill in the fridge for a minimum of 1 hour or overnight before slicing.

author: thenutritionreporter
caption:
ONE MORE TIME FOR THOSE AT THE BACK üëè üëè üëè No matter how ‚Äúclean‚Äù your diet is, if your stress levels are high, your body isn‚Äôt getting the full benefits of what you eat. 

When you‚Äôre constantly stressed, cortisol dominates, your digestion slows, and nutrient absorption drops. Your ‚Äúperfect‚Äù meal won‚Äôt fuel you the way it could. 

That‚Äôs because your rest and digest nervous system ‚Äì the part of your body that allows you to properly break down food and absorb nutrients ‚Äì can‚Äôt do its job when stress is in control.

Food matters, yes, but so does how you live. Taking a moment to slow down, breathe, or just give yourself a break isn‚Äôt indulgent ‚Äì it‚Äôs necessary for your gut, your hormones, and your overall wellbeing üíõüåü‚ú®üí´

Sometimes the healthiest choice isn‚Äôt on your plate, it‚Äôs giving yourself permission to rest. You‚Äôve got this ü©∑

caption:
INGREDIENTS:

MARINADE (Per pot)
1 tsp miso paste
2 tsp soy sauce (sodium reduced if possible)
¬Ω tsp gochujang
1 tsp optional olive oil
¬Ω tsp smoked paprika
¬Ω tsp garlic powder

FOR 3 JARS:
1 serving of glass noodles per jar 
1 block extra firm tofu (280g)
1 cup edamame (defrost before if using frozen)
2 medium carrots, peeled into ribbons
2 stalks spring onion, sliced
1 head of bok choy, sliced

METHOD:
1. Cut the tofu into small cubes and bake for 15 minutes in the air-fryer or in the oven. Meanwhile, chop the veggies. 
3. Assemble the pots by mixing the marinade ingredients in the bottom. 
4. Divide the crispy tofu equally between the jars, then add the edamame, veggies and finally a serving of dry noodles to each pot. Push it down and cover with a lid. Use a heat-proof, sealable, air-tight container/jar.
5. Store in the fridge for up to 3-4 days. When serving, pour over hot water, make sure to fully cover up until the noodles. Let it soak for 3-5 minutes until the noodles cook through. Mix and enjoy!

author: thenutritionreporter
caption:
THE ONE YOU‚ÄôVE ALL BEEN WAITING FOR: COLLAGEN CHAT (Girl Science Edition) ü©∑

First up, collagen is important. It‚Äôs what keeps your skin bouncy, joints cushioned, and tissues strong. Your body makes collagen, but rom your mid-20s, that production starts to dip ‚Äì and drops faster post-menopause thanks to hormonal changes.

DO YOU NEED TO TAKE A COLLAGEN SUPPLEMENT?

Collagen supplements don‚Äôt ‚Äútop up‚Äù your collagen directly. They‚Äôre broken down into small peptides that signal your body to make more, but only if your body‚Äôs in the right state to respond. That generally comes from you sleeping well, eating a balanced diet with enough protein and managing your stress, Without those foundations, the signal‚Äôs weak ‚Äì and your collagen powder probably won‚Äôt do much.
Where collagen actually delivers:

üíûJoints: Hydrolysed or type II collagen can help reduce joint pain and slow cartilage breakdown (especially if osteoarthritis runs in your family).
üåüSkin: Evidence is mixed. High-quality, independent studies show minimal benefit for elasticity or hydration.
üíÖHair & nails: Not much science here yet.

Takehome message: collagen can support you, but it‚Äôs not a miracle. Focus on your foundations first ‚Äì balanced nutrition, sleep, and stress management ‚Äì and collagen becomes the cherry on top, not the whole sundae üçí

author: thenutritionreporter
caption:
CREATINE FOR WOMEN ‚Äî WHAT THE SCIENCE SAYS üß†üí™

Creatine is no longer just for gym bros ‚Äî it‚Äôs one of the most researched and effective supplements for women too.

ü©∑ Premenopause: Studies show 3‚Äì5 g/day can improve muscle strength, exercise performance, and even support mood and cognition. Women tend to have lower baseline creatine stores, so supplementation can help fill that gap.

ü©∑ Menopause: Creatine (alone or with resistance training) may help maintain muscle, bone health, and cognitive function as oestrogen declines. Higher doses ‚Äî up to 0.3 g/kg/day ‚Äî have shown benefits in postmenopausal women.

ü©∑ Pregnancy: Animal and early human data suggest creatine supports energy demands and may have neuroprotective effects for the baby ‚Äî but research in humans is still limited. Dietary sources (like fish and meat) are safe, but supplements aren‚Äôt routinely recommended just yet.

OVERALL: Creatine is safe and effective for most women outside of pregnancy when taken at standard doses (3‚Äì5 g/day). Always choose a high-quality, third-party-tested product.

üìö Sources: International Society of Sports Nutrition (ISSN), Smith-Ryan et al., 2021; Forbes et al., 2022; Solis et al., 2023.

caption:
DOUBLE CHOCOLATE & MACADAMIA NUT BROOKIES ü§éüíõ

Brownie meets cookie, and it‚Äôs love at first sight. They are simply inseparable and they complement each other despite their differences. One brings cacao and fudginess to the table while the other brings fibre and plant protein. It‚Äôs a match made in the oven.

INGREDIENTS:

BROWNIE LAYER
3/4 cup almond or peanut butter (slightly chilled if very runny)
¬º cup coconut sugar (or maple syrup)
2 flax eggs (2 tbsp flaxseed + 4-5 tbsp water)
‚Öì cup cocoa powder
¬Ω tsp baking powder
pinch of salt

COOKIE LAYER
1 can chickpeas (drained & rinsed)
2 tbsp almond or peanut butter
2 tsp + 1 tsp maple syrup
1 tsp pure vanilla extract
1/2 tsp baking powder
1/3 cup oat flour
50g white chocolate chips or chopped chocolate
handful of macadamia nuts
pinch of salt

METHOD:
Pre-heat oven to 175C or 160C with fan. Line a loaf tin with parchment paper.
Make the flax egg and let it sit for 10 minutes.
Make the brownie by mixing the nut butter, coconut sugar and the flax egg until smooth. Mix in remaining ingredients and transfer into the tin. Push down with a metal spoon. 
Make the cookie layer: blend all ingredients together in a food processor until smooth. Transfer the batter into a bowl and mix in the oat flour followed by chopped white chocolate and macadamia nuts. 
Spread the batter on top of the brownie batter layer and push down with a metal spoon.
Bake in the oven for 20-25 minutes. Edges should be set and the centre lightly soft. Once out of the oven, sprinkle some sea salt on top.
Cool completely before slicing into 14 squares.

caption:
HEALTHY CHOCOLATE TRUFFLE CAKE
In honour of @britishbakeoff chocolate week!! 
 
INGREDIENTS: 

2 ¬Ω cups cooked sweet potato (about 2 large) 
1 ¬Ω cups ground almonds (almond flour) 
¬æ cup cocoa powder (unsweetened) 
¬Ω cup tahini (or almond butter for a sweeter flavour) 
¬Ω cup maple syrup (or honey) 
¬º cup coconut oil, melted 
1 tsp baking powder 
1 tsp vanilla extract 
Pinch sea salt 
100g 85% dark chocolate (melted) 

OPTIONAL TOPPINGS:

Melted chocolate (add a little coconut oil for extra glossiness)
Berries (I used raspberries)
Sprinkling of chopped nuts (I chose pistachios) 

METHOD: 

1. Preheat oven to 180¬∞C (170¬∞C fan) and line a springform cake tin with baking paper.

2. Wash the sweet potatoes, poke them with a fork and put them into the pre-heated oven for around 40-50 minutes until cooked. Once the potatoes are cooled, peel and add the flesh into a food processor. Blend until smooth. 

3.Melt the chocolate in the microwave or using a double boiler. 

4. In a large bowl, combine the blended sweet potato with the rest of the ingredients, including the melted chocolate and stir until thick and glossy. Or you can add all the ingredients into the food processor if it is big enough. 

5. Pour the batter into the cake tin and using the back of a spatula or metal spoon, press the batter down and smooth it out. 

6. Bake for 30-35 mins (should be fudgy, not dry). 

7. Leave to cool completely before removing from the tin. You can also place it in the fridge at this point to firm up a little more so it is easier to slice. Cover in melted chocolate and top with any additional ingredients you like - berries and nuts are a great combo.

üçÖ high protein üçÖ anti-bloatingüçÖ gut friendlyüçÖ hormone friendlyüçÖ easy to make

INGREDIENTS:
‚Üí 150g raw chicken
‚Üí 1 onion
‚Üí 1 tomato
‚Üí 1/2 garlic head 
‚Üí 50g dry pasta
‚Üí 1 tsp olive oil 
‚Üí 30 ml light cream or 40g Greek yogurt
‚Üí 1 tbsp of parmesan cheese 
‚Üí fresh parsley and basil
‚Üí salt, black pepper, thyme, Italian seasoning, chili flakes

METHOD:
‚Üí Preheat your oven to 200¬∞C / 390¬∞F. Slice onion into thin strips, chop tomato and halve the garlic head horizontally‚Üí Place everything on a baking tray. Add the chicken breast on top of the veggies and drizzle ¬Ω tsp olive oil over everything. Season with:salt, black pepper, thyme, Italian seasoning and chili flakes. 
‚Üí Bake for 25‚Äì35 minute until the onions are soft and golden, the tomato is juicy and the garlic is creamy inside. The chicken should be cooked through and easy to shred.
‚ÜíWhile it bakes, cook your pasta and save ¬Ω cup pasta water.
‚Üí Remove tray from the oven and shred the chicken with two forks. Squeeze the roasted garlic cloves out of the head.
‚Üí Add the roasted onions, tomato and the garlic cloves to a large pan, pour in a splash of pasta water, then stir in Greek yogurt or light cream to make it creamy‚Üí If you prefer a smoother sauce: you can blend this step, totally up to you.
‚Üí Add the shredded chicken and cooked pasta to the pan, toss everything until creamy. Finish with parmesan, lots of fresh basil, parsley and black pepper.

caption:
this is your sign to glow up in 2026 ü§ç follow @nicolinanunes for more

üçì put ‚ÄúRECIPE‚Äù below for my healthy cookbook üíö 

The biggest fitness scam I fell into? Thinking you can out train a bad diet ‚ù§Ô∏è‚Äçü©π

When I was overweight I thought my problem was workouts and discipline, so I trained harder, longer, more. I was training 6-7 times a week, including HIITs, lots of cardio and yes my body barely changed. I was so exhausted, frustrated and still not seeing the results I always wanted! 

When I focused on how I nourish my body not just how I move it, I lost +46lbs! üò≠

‚ú® I started eating the foods I loved
‚ú® I stopped overtraining and train only for 3-4 workouts a week
‚ú® I prioritized protein, healthy fats, fiber, not ‚Äúdiet healthy foods‚Äù that left me hungry!
‚ú® I stopped skipping breakfast and living off snacks and coffee
‚ú® I built meals that satisfied me, stabilized my hormones and balanced my cravings
‚ú® I stopped doing hours of cardio and started walking instead 
‚ú® I started training less and LIVING MORE üíñ

So if you are stuck thinking you just need more discipline or more workouts, please hear me: you don‚Äôt need to do more or even harder!

author: georgiaheins
caption:
This lowers your blood sugar faster than any supplement

When you walk, your muscles basically turn into a sponge - they soak up glucose instead of storing it, which helps your blood sugar, sleep and mood.

Good analogy? Yes
Is it also kinda what‚Äôs actually happening? Also yes

When you walk after you eat, your muscles pull more glucose out of your bloodstream and use it for energy or store it as glycogen, instead of leaving it to spike your blood sugar or be stored as fat

More movement =
1. Fewer crashes
2. Fewer cravings
3. More stable mood
4. Better sleep

You don‚Äôt need another ‚Äúblood sugar hack‚Äù in a bottle

You probably just need a 10-15 minute walk after meals

Share this with a friend who thinks berberine is the answer üòÖ

P.S. Supplements like berberine can be helpful if you‚Äôve got something like PCOS or insulin resistance - but they work best with the basics (like walking + balanced meals), not instead of them

author: apurvatilwani
caption:
Yoga is for the mind, breath, and pranic flow, not an alternative to physical strengthening.

I have personally met many yogis who carry severe injuries from their asana practice. Not because yoga is harmful, but because it was treated as something it was never meant to be.

If your body has pain, weakness, or a specific condition, strengthen it using the right tools first. Yoga will not magically cure the body of all diseases and illnesses. Yes, yoga definitely helps in healing, but healing cannot and should not be the primary goal of the practice.

Don‚Äôt burden yoga with expectations it was never designed to carry.
Respect the practice. Respect the body.

Sharing a snippet from my recent workshop in Chennai.

author: apurvatilwani
caption:
Welcome to my Glow Up series‚Äîa journey through all my transformation videos, from where I started to where I am today!

Part 7

When I began calisthenics back in 2022, I was a complete noob. I could barely manage a few push-ups and pull-ups. Skills like the pullover or back lever felt impossible. I still remember hitting my knees so hard while trying to achieve my first pullover‚Äîdoing everything wrong, but refusing to quit.

Fast forward to 2025‚Äîconsistency, discipline, and relentless practice changed everything. The bars that once intimidated me are now my playground.

It‚Äôs proof that with patience and hard work, the ‚Äúimpossible‚Äù slowly becomes second nature.

Keep showing up. Your glow up is loading.

Last week‚Ä¶ my brain forgot how to fall asleep. I was overstressed..

PhD stress. 
Travel stress 
Cortisol sky-high.
Panic mode. Why? 
Every night. 

And I know this:
Sleep is active brain repair.
It‚Äôs when your brain cleans itself, stores memories, resets your emotions, and protects long-term cognitive health.

Chronic poor sleep can shrink the hippocampus- memory centreand increase dementia risk.

So I turned to something gentle and evidence-based: slow eye movements before sleep 

A 2021 study of 120 adults found that this technique significantly improved sleep quality (measured by PSQI).
(Hu et al., 2021)

And for the first time I slept deeply.

My nervous system finally exhaled.

Try moving your eyes very slowly, eyelids closed before you go to sleep. Or if you wake up in the middle of a night‚Ä¶
üëÅÔ∏è Left ‚Üí Right
üëÅÔ∏è Up ‚Üí Down
üëÅÔ∏è Slow circles both directions

3 -5 minutes ‚Ä¢ no pressure

It calms the brainstem.
It signals melatonin release.
It tells your brain: ‚ÄúYou are safe. Sleep now.‚Äù

Protect your sleep.
Protect your brain.

You deserve to wake up restored. 

Save this post to try tonight üß†

Share it with someone who needs rest 

Agnieszka

author: agnieszka.butter
caption:
Success begins in your brain ‚Äî not in motivation.

This figure-8 eye exercise trains your brain to focus, adapt, and persist ‚Äî the foundations of neuroplasticity and sustainable success.

Follow the figure 8 with your eyes

Add a challenge:
‚ùå Count odd numbers backward from 11
You‚Äôre activating your prefrontal cortex (focus and strategy) and cerebellum (precision and timing).

Add another challenge:
‚ùå Count even numbers backward from 10
You‚Äôre syncing both brain hemispheres and boosting your prefrontal cortex ‚Äî your inner CEO.

My tip: 
Use it daily ‚Äî before doctor‚Äôs appointments, presentations, creative work, studying, or decisions that require clarity, focus and confidence.

Because success is not mindset alone ‚Äî it‚Äôs neuroscience in action.

Question: 
Are you training your brain for success?

I would love to hear from you.

Xx Agnieszka

author: francesca.golfetto
caption:
Have you ever felt like life moves so fast that you suddenly stop and think, wait‚Ä¶ how did I get here?
Lately, that‚Äôs been me.

We all try to take control in different ways - some by planning, some through food, some by keeping things perfectly tidy.
For me, it always starts with my body.

When everything moves too fast, I come back to my practice- to my breath, my sensations and feelings.
It‚Äôs where I find my ground again.
My body reminds me where I am, what I hold, and what I can release.

Sometimes it‚Äôs not about having it all figured out, but about understanding small glimpses through the practice‚Ä¶
and that‚Äôs what I hope to share through my teachings. ‚ú®

.

.

author: francesca.golfetto
caption:
The past few days I practiced in a more technical way, focusing on deeper flexibility work, more structure.
And honestly? My body felt sore, tight, and a little stubborn. It left me feeling frustrated. ü´£üëÄ

So today, I dropped the structure.
I went back to my own style - fluid, slinky, intuitive - and suddenly it all made sense.
My body let go. My breath returned. Everything opened up again.

It reminded me that we move through phases.
There were times when deep flexibility drills felt like magic for me, and I know they will again.
But right now, this is the season of softness, of feeling, of flowing.
And I‚Äôm loving it.

.

.

Here‚Äôs the chocolate chip recipe in case that‚Äôs more interesting to you

2c flour
1 1/4 c cake flour 
2 tsp baking powder 
1/4 tsp baking soda 
1/4 tsp  salt 
1 c cold butter
2/3 c packed brown sugar 
2/3 c granulated sugar 
2 c chocolate chips
1 c walnuts
2 large eggs

whisk together flours, baking powder, baking soda, and salt.
In a separate bowl mix the butter with the sugar until creamy. Add chocolate chips and walnuts and mix.
Add the flour mixture until it‚Äôs evenly crumbly, then add the egg and keep mixing until it‚Äôs one large cookie ball.
Separate the giant ball into smaller balls, slightly smaller than your fist. Place on a tray and put in the fridge overnight to chill and slightly dehydrate.
Bake at 375 for about 25 minutes and let cool or you can eat it immediately like I did and burn your tongue.

Also, I didn‚Äôt know you could make creme br√ªl√©e at home either, but here is the recipe in case you have a blow torch:
Ingredients
* 2 ¬Ω cups heavy cream
* 1 vanilla bean pod (or 1 tsp vanilla extract)
* 1 ¬º cups sugar, divided
* 5 egg yolks
* Pinch salt
* Berries (optional)
1. Heat oven to 325¬∞F. Place ramekins in baking pan.
2. Warm cream in saucepan until bubbles show at edges. Split vanilla bean, scrape seeds into cream. Remove from heat.
3. Make vanilla sugar: mix ¬æ cup sugar with vanilla pod.
4. Whisk yolks with ¬Ω cup sugar until pale.
5. Slowly add warm cream to yolks, stirring constantly.
6. Pour custard into ramekins, leaving space at top.
7. Fill baking pan with hot water around ramekins. Bake 35 minutes, until almost set.
8. Cool in water 20 minutes. Remove, dry, wrap. Chill at least 2 hours.
9. To serve, top with 2 tbsp vanilla sugar. Torch until caramelized. Let cool 2 minutes. Add berries, eat at least five of them.

author: iamsarahsnow
caption:
I have found that you don‚Äôt create when the conditions are perfect, you create when you have something to say. 

Yummy shakshuka recipe 

Ingredients 
2 Tbsp olive oil
¬Ω small yellow onion, diced
1 medium red bell pepper, chopped
2 cloves fresh garlic, minced
¬º tsp kosher salt
¬Ω tsp smoked paprika
¬º tsp cumin
¬º tsp pepper
1 (28 oz) can whole peeled tomatoes
1 Tbsp fresh cilantro chopped, plus more for serving
1 Tbsp fresh parsley, chopped, plus more for serving
4-6 eggs
Sourdough bread, toasted, for serving, optional

Step 1
In a large skillet over medium heat, add the oil, onion and bell pepper and cook, stirring frequently for 3-4 minutes, until the onion has softened and bell pepper is tender. 
¬†
Step 2
Add the garlic, salt, paprika, cumin, and pepper, and cook for 30-60 seconds until fragrant.
¬†
Step 3
Add the tomatoes and their juices, and break them using a wooden spoon. Stir in the cilantro and parsley and bring to a simmer.
¬†
Step 4
Create 4-6 little nests for the eggs in the sauce using a wooden spoon, and crack an egg into each hole. Cook for 8-12 minutes or until eggs are cooked to desired doneness.
¬†
Step 5
Garnish with additional fresh cilantro and parsley as desired, and serve with warm toasted sourdough bread. 

Enjoy!

author: iamsarahsnow
caption:
@iamsarahsnow shares her 5Ô∏è‚É£ ingredients for creating engaging content with intention:

1. The Hook ü™ù
The hook should have visual movement within the first three seconds. It should also build curiosity and not confusion.

2. The Storyline üìñ
For classic storytelling, make sure your story unfolds on a timeline (today, last week, last year). For educational storytelling, make sure your information is TANGIBLE and not fluff.

3. Sound Design üì£
Listen to your video without looking at it. Is it still enjoyable and clear? Is any of the audio distracting? Pro tip: add foley! It will make your videos feel like a movie.

4. The Captions üìù
Make sure your captions reflect HOW you‚Äôre speaking and are EASY to read. You should be able to watch the video without sound and still understand the inflections based on how the captions transition and are sized.

5. The Footage üé•
This is probably the area I spend the most time on. Make sure your footage serves the story and is satisfying to watch, whether that be the actual content or the composition/lighting/color correction.

author: williamscxtt
caption:
Perspective.

Everything you think will make you happy is bullshit.

I just moved into a nicer apartment and I already don‚Äôt give a fuck about it.

Like yeah, it‚Äôs bigger. Nicer kitchen. All that shit.

But after two weeks? It‚Äôs just the place I eat, sleep and work. That‚Äôs it.

And this is the same with everything I‚Äôve bought.

I used to think a faster car would change my life. Better steering wheel. Nicer interior. I‚Äôd be happier.

But you know what happens? You drive it for two weeks and it just becomes your car.

The LED lights you thought were sick? Don‚Äôt even notice them anymore.

it‚Äôs all about your perspective, If you‚Äôve never had a nice car, and I gave you a BMW, you‚Äôd lose your fucking mind. Best day of your life. 10/10 excitement.

But if you already owned a Lambo? That same BMW would feel like a downgrade. You‚Äôd be like ‚Äúoh cool, thanks I guess.‚Äù Maybe a 5/10.

Same car. Same price. But your excitement depends entirely on what you‚Äôre used to, and your perspective.

And I‚Äôm not saying don‚Äôt have goals or buy nice shit. But don‚Äôt think it‚Äôs gonna make you happy.

Cause I‚Äôve been chasing this nice stuff for years
And the truth is, it all feels the same after a couple weeks.

author: williamscxtt
caption:
You don‚Äôt need therapy, you need the gym.

Every guy I know who‚Äôs turned their life around didn‚Äôt do it in a therapy session. They did it in the gym.

And This will piss some people off but the gym has done more for my mental health than any fucking therapy ever will for you.
See, therapy tells you to talk about your problems. Process your emotions. Understand your trauma.

And that might work for some people.

But most men don‚Äôt need to talk about it. They need to do something about it.

The gym doesn‚Äôt ask you how you feel. It doesn‚Äôt care about your childhood. It just gives you something real to focus on, that improves your life. 

Whether You‚Äôre angry, sad overthinking your problems or Your life‚Äôs falling apart? You can Go to the gym. And for an hour, the only thing that matters is the weight in front of you.

That‚Äôs what fixes you. Not talking. Not processing. Action.
So I‚Äôm not saying therapy is useless. I‚Äôm saying the gym is cheaper, faster, and actually works.

author: beautyshamans
caption:
Fact: Muscles respond to exercise, they become bigger and stronger which creates lift and volume to the face. 

Fun fact: The face is the only area of the body where muscles are directly attached to skin so where the muscles go, skin goes too. 

Recommendation: You must be very careful and mindful that you‚Äôre not inadvertently creating wrinkles when you practice healthier facial expressions or facial lifts. 

This is one very common mistake I see and I don‚Äôt want you to make it too! Not only will it potentially make crows feet worse, but you won‚Äôt see as much lift in the cheeks or softening of the nasolabial folds as you would like. 

Learn how to do it right the first time and you‚Äôll be set for success. 

If you need more guided rituals, join the Skin Within Studio - we do a ton of these holding poses together. Go to beautyshamans.com or link in bio. I‚Äôll see you in the Studio! 

#faceyoga #beautyshamans

author: beautyshamans
caption:
My remedy for droopy brows and hooded lids that really works! 

That photo of my eyes is from when I was about 22. I hated that I always looked puffy and tired, but I thought for the longest time that there was nothing I could do. While I have lost some of my ‚Äúbaby fat‚Äù I also worked on opening my eyes and brows as much as I could after learning about facial anatomy as a nurse injector. 

I drew upon these ideas to help me form a protocol: 

- Botox injections (which relax muscles) on the outer brow will lift the brows. So why not just relax them manually? 

- My husband taught me about resistance training and how that can create a lift in muscles. 

- Lymphatic drainage is something I studied throughout my esthetics career - drain the ‚Äúwater‚Äù and everything opens up. 

- Fascia manipulation is something that‚Äôs new to the modern beauty space but it‚Äôs actually been used in healing and longevity for centuries. 

- Scalp and neck flexibility are huge indicators of how well your entire body and face move. Once that stiffness settles in, everything droops. 

If you‚Äôre a Studio member, the full class is available now! 

Go to beautyshamans.com or tap the link in bio to join my ritual style classes - get ready to learn a lot, reset your nervous system, love your face and transform from the inside out.

Repost! This info has been helpful for many, so I wanted to share it again in case you missed it. 

Fillers may be a silver bullet, but only for a short time. There will come a day when filler for marionette lines just doesn‚Äôt work anymore (I‚Äôve seen it in my practice as a former injector).

For long term results, what works is consistent care and attention to the facial tissue (muscle, fascia, lymph, skin, etc).

In my professional opinion, you can do facial exercise, or you can do facial exercise + a little filler to boost, but you cannot rely on filler alone and expect facial longevity.

author: beautyshamans
caption:
My remedy for droopy brows and hooded lids that really works. That photo of my eyes is from when I was about 22. I hated that I always looked puffy and tired, but I thought for the longest time that there was nothing I could do. While I have lost some of my ‚Äúbaby fat‚Äù I also worked on opening my eyes and brows as much as I could after learning about facial anatomy as a nurse injector. 

I drew upon these ideas to help me form a protocol: 

- Botox injections (which relax muscles) on the outer brow will lift the brows. So why not just relax them manually? 
- My husband taught me about resistance training and how that can create a lift in muscles. 
- Lymphatic drainage is something I studied throughout my esthetic career - drain the ‚Äúwater‚Äù and everything opens up 
- Fascia manipulation is something that‚Äôs new to the modern beauty space but it‚Äôs actually been used in healing and longevity for centuries. 
- Scalp and neck flexibility are huge indicators of how well your entire body and face move. Once that stiffness settles in, everything droops. 

 If you‚Äôre a Studio member, I‚Äôll be uploading this full length class to the video library soon. 

Go to beautyshamans.com or tap the link in bio to join my ritual style classes - get ready to learn a lot, reset your nervous system, love your face and transform from the inside out. 

#beautyshamans #skinwithinstudio #faceyoga #skincare #hoodedlids #guasha #skinwithin #facialfitness #facialmassage

author: beautyshamans
caption:
Fillers may be a silver bullet, but only for a short time. There will come a day when filler for marionette lines just doesn‚Äôt work anymore (I‚Äôve seen it in my practice as a former injector). 

For long term results, what works is consistent care and attention to the facial tissue (muscle, fascia, lymph, skin, etc). 

In my professional opinion, you can do facial exercise, or you can do facial exercise + a little filler to boost, but you cannot rely on filler alone and expect facial longevity. 

Tools and classes at beautyshamans.com ‚ô•Ô∏è 

#faceyoga #beautyshamans #facialexercise #marionettelines

author: beautyshamans
caption:
Comment ‚ÄúJOIN‚Äù and I‚Äôll send you the direct link to the full 24 minute class where we address marionette lines, jowls and nasolabial folds! 

When I was a nurse injector, the two most commonly requested areas to ‚Äúfix‚Äù were marionette lines and nasolabial folds. If you are open to injections, cool, no judgement here. They have a place in the cosmetic world, and I‚Äôve seen them make many people very happy, and fillers will absolutely help temporarily. 

But I‚Äôll be honest, you can‚Äôt use fillers in these areas forever, the product may never fully dissolve, so they eventually make the face look bottom heavy and puffy if you‚Äôre not doing some kind of work on your own too. (FYI an experienced injector can place botox in the DOA muscle which will help this muscle to relax, which yields a slight lift around the mouth). 

To correct this area naturally, we want to mimic what botox and filler do - we need to relax the DAO muscle (massage), release the downward pull on the mouth (face yoga stretches), relieve the area of fluid retention (lymph drainage), and encourage more blood flow and lift to the mouth region. I‚Äôve seen this work for my clients and I‚Äôve seen it work for myself. 

Results are inevitable, but they are heavily influenced by your consistency. 

In my Skin Within Studio we practice lots of these movements together using facial massage, face yoga, gua sha and reflexology! All classes are 5-30 minutes long and all you have to do is follow along and copy what I‚Äôm doing. It‚Äôs that simple. 

Remember, skincare products are for skin. Facial manipulation is for the face. I have everything you need on my site, beautyshamans.com ‚ô•Ô∏è 

#beautyshamans #faceyoga #marionettelines #facialmassage #facialfitness #fascia

author: beautyshamans
caption:
Just trying to clarify misleading information I keep seeing because I know a lot of you feel confused.¬†

My intention here is not to call anyone out or make anyone look bad (why I covered the face and handle).¬†

But let‚Äôs get something straight; working with the lymphatic system is one of MANY ways to lift¬†the face. It is not the only way (and I beg you to be wary of anyone who says it‚Äôs the ‚Äúonly‚Äù way, they are probably just trying to sell you something). There are in fact many modalities and techniques that uplift the face, some examples are (and not limited¬†to); face yoga stretches, face lifting¬†exercises, gua sha, massage, SLEEP, cupping, reflexology, face taping, mouth taping, being a good human, botox, filler, facelift, threads, plastic surgery, etc... I don‚Äôt use or practice all of these methods, but that doesn‚Äôt mean they aren‚Äôt effective.¬†

When it comes to ANYTHING in your life; your skincare, facial care, workout routine, diet, finances...whatever¬†it is...I encourage you to consider something Bruce Lee once said - ‚Äúabsorb what is useful, discard what is useless, and add what is uniquely your own.‚Äù When it comes to your face, don‚Äôt allow any ‚Äúleader‚Äù or ‚Äúinfluencer‚Äù or even any expert to become your god. The only thing you need is a little guidance to get started, followed heavily by your intuition and your inner wisdom. As you get to know your face, you start to understand what works best for you and what you enjoy doing. Be open to everything (all modalities)until you find the right mix for you. 

I‚Äôm thrilled so many practitioners are joining the facial fitness movement, we are an emerging force in the beauty and wellness space and the fact that more teachers and experts are popping up is not something to feel intimidated by or insecure about, it is something to celebrate because it means we as a niche group of facial fitness pioneers are making progress and shifting the way men and women all over the world think and feel about aging beautifully. When some practitioners want to say their way is the only way, it makes me wonder if they actually want to be part of this growing community or if they‚Äôre in it just for themselves. #facialfitness #guasha

caption:
The knee relies heavily on the integrity of its surrounding tendons‚Äîfrom the quadriceps and patellar tendons to the hamstrings and the pes anserine. When these structures develop fascial adhesions, they can create pain and movement restrictions.

In this video, in addition to tendon-focused massage, I also perform patellar mobilization‚Äîa technique that helps release the tissues around the patella, improve patellar glide, and reduce unnecessary joint pressure.

The goal is to restore natural knee mechanics and reduce tendon-related discomfort.
