author: iranmassage.co
caption:
Tightness in the teres minor, infraspinatus, and supraspinatus muscles is one of the common causes of limited shoulder mobility and discomfort in the back of the shoulder.
When these muscles stay shortened, lifting the arm or moving it overhead becomes difficult and often feels restricted.

In this video, I demonstrate a simple chair stretch with no equipment that helps to:
	‚Ä¢	Release tension in these three muscles
	‚Ä¢	Improve shoulder range of motion
	‚Ä¢	Reduce discomfort at the end range of elevation

This stretch works best when you:
	‚Ä¢	Keep your breathing slow and relaxed
	‚Ä¢	Avoid hiking the shoulders and allow the back of the shoulder to open
	‚Ä¢	Maintain a gentle, controlled stretch without sharp pain

If you struggle with shoulder stiffness or feel tightness in the posterior shoulder, this can be a highly effective daily routine.

caption:
The lymphatic system is a crucial component in maintaining fluid balance and tissue immunity.
During lymphatic drainage massage with Gua Sha, controlled and directional mechanical stimulation enhances lymph flow along anatomical pathways.
This process promotes interstitial fluid clearance, improves lymphatic return, and reduces the accumulation of inflammatory metabolites.
In this approach, Gua Sha serves as a therapeutic tool for lymphodynamic modulation and optimization of microcirculatory function, rather than merely an aesthetic technique.

author: iranmassage.co
caption:
Specialized massage of the orbicularis oculi muscle enhances blood circulation, reduces muscular tension, and may help improve periorbital wrinkles, particularly lateral canthal lines.
These wrinkles are not solely due to orbicularis oculi contractions, but also result from the combined action of other facial muscles (such as the zygomatic and frontalis) and tissue changes like collagen loss, elastin reduction, and skin thinning.
Through mechanical stimulation and improved tissue metabolism, this technique supports skin vitality and periorbital rejuvenation.

author: iranmassage.co
caption:
In this video, fascial release is applied to the hamstring muscles and tendons.
Adhesions in the fascia of this region can lead to reduced intermuscular glide and limited fascial mobility,
which often manifest as persistent posterior thigh pain or restricted hip flexion due to excessive tension in the posterior chain.

Fascial release with tools, by stimulating mechanoreceptors and improving interfascial flow, helps restore normal tissue function and reduce functional pain.

author: iranmassage.co
caption:
Percussion (Tapotement) techniques are more than rhythmic strikes; they act as a controlled neuromuscular stimulus.
This method creates rapid mechanical vibration, which helps:

‚Ä¢ Increase local blood flow
‚Ä¢ Reduce superficial fascial adhesions
‚Ä¢ Improve neuromuscular recruitment
‚Ä¢ Enhance muscular alertness during the warm-up phase

Percussion is ideal when we need to activate a muscle, overcome neural inhibition, or prepare it for corrective movement patterns.
Note: High-intensity tapotement is not recommended during acute inflammation or post-exercise recovery phases.

üéØ Massage: Beyond the Skin

Mechanical stimulation during massage affects not only the skin and fascia but also directly impacts muscle fibers and tendinous structures.

	‚Ä¢	Reduce muscle tension and spasms
	‚Ä¢	Enhance tendon flexibility and decrease the risk of injury

To make these effects clearer, I use illustration and artwork to show that massage is not merely a surface-level process; it is a direct engagement with muscle and tendon function.

author: iranmassage.co
caption:
Frown lines are not just superficial wrinkles; they result from hyperactivity of the Corrugator Supercilii combined with involvement of the Procerus muscle. Repetitive contraction of these muscles pulls the glabellar skin inward and downward, gradually forming deep and persistent creases.

In professional glabellar massage, the goal is not merely skin relaxation.
It focuses on retraining muscular patterns, reducing excessive tone, improving fascial glide, and ultimately enhancing local tissue perfusion.
A precise understanding of the anatomy is essential for safe and effective technique application.

In hand massage, precision is everything.
The thenar and hypothenar regions control the fine movements of the fingers,
while the flexor tendons of the thumb and index finger act like neural cables connecting directly to the forearm muscles.

‚ú® Deep massage in these areas releases fascial adhesions, improves tendon glide, and enhances neuromuscular coordination.
